e_2010skca8.txt,"Fulltext of judgment follows: Following the conviction of the respondent on a charge of trafficking in morphine contrary to section 5(1) of the Controlled Drugs and Substances Act, the prosecutor asked the sentencing judge to make a DNA order under section 487.051(3) of the Criminal Code. The judge declined to do so for the reason this was the respondent's first drug offence and she had no record of violence. With respect, we are of the opinion the judge erred in declining to make the order. The error lay in the judge's failure to have regard for the offender's record as a wholeÃ¹she has 53 prior convictionsÃ¹and to have adequate regard for the objectives of section 487.051 as identified in R. v. Briggs 2001 CanLII 24113 (ON C.A.), (2001), 45 C.R. (5th) 99 (Ont. C.A.). In light of the nature of the respondent's current offence, her lengthy record, her history of recidivism, and the relatively modest impact an order would have on her privacy and security interests, we are satisfied an order should have been made. Accordingly, and in the best interests of the administration of justice, there will be an order under section 487.051(3) in Form 5.04 for the taking of bodily samples from the respondent. If any directions should be required in relation to the execution of the order, the parties are given leave to informally apply for such directions through the Registrar's office.","Following the conviction of the respondent on a charge of trafficking in morphine contrary to s. 5(1) of the Controlled Drugs and Substances Act, the prosecutor asked the sentencing judge to make a DNA order under s. 487.051(3) under the Criminal Code. The judge declined to do so for the reason this was the respondent's first drug offence and she had no record of violence. With respect to the issue of the order, the Court of Appeal is of the opinion the judge erred in declining to make the order. The error lay in the judge's failure to have regard for the offender's record as a whole (she has 53 prior convictions) and to have adequate regard for her objectives of s.487.05(3). In light of the nature of the offender, her current offence, her lengthy record, her history of recidivism, and the relatively modest impact an order would have on her privacy and security interests, we are satisfied an order should have been made. Accordingly, and in the best interests of the administration of justice, there will be an order under ss.487(3)(a) in Form 5.04 for the taking of bodily samples from the respondent."
2_2005skpc38.txt,"The accused is charged with driving without due care and attention contrary to s. 44(1) of the Highway Traffic Act. A pedestrian was crossing a road adjacent to a parking lot and, while walking directly in front of a stopped vehicle, was struck by the vehicle when it rolled forward. HELD: The accused is not guilty. The court accepted the accused's evidence that his vehicle rolled forward only a short distance of not more than one foot and not at a fast or accelerated speed and that the pedestrian was crossing outside of the cross walk and that the accused applied his brakes as soon as he saw the pedestrian. The accused did exercise due diligence.","The accused was charged with driving without due care and attention contrary to s. 44(1) of the Highway Traffic Act. The accused was on duty in a marked police car when the accused's vehicle rolled forward and hit the complainant. The complainant crossed the street outside of the cross-walk and called for other police officers. At trial, the Crown called three witnesses who testified that the accused was travelling very fast (over 25 km/h). The defence suggested the accused had an oblique motive for thinking that the complainant was being insolent and returning to set him straight. The Crown argued the accused should have simply continued driving. The officer testified that as he was leaving Super Store, he passed in front of a stopped vehicle, which turned out to be the defendant's vehicle. The defence then called four witnesses: Michael Rostotski, Corporal Pelzer, Constable Kinellson and Mr. Tyndall. They accepted that the vehicle only moved less than one foot, and didn't accelerate or move forward quickly. They also accepted that neither seat belt nor a raised voice in speaking to the officer was locked upon striking the accused. They both testified that their position in the vehicle was near the intersection where the collision occurred. The issue to be determined was whether the Crown has proved that the driving by the accused constituted carelessness applying an objective test in assessing carelessness and whether it has then shown on a balance of probabilities that it exercised due diligence in the context of the circumstances encountered. The actions of the accused which could be considered careless are, firstly, the speed at which the vehicle rolled past the complainant, and secondly, the manner in which it crossed the road. The second part of the Sault Ste. Marie test is whether the accused exercised due care or attention. HELD: The accused is guilty of the charge. 1) The officer's evidence that he did not touch the accelerator, not touching the brake, and rolled forward striking the complainant less than a short distance. This is insufficient to conclude that the actual speed of the vehicle is at most one foot. Given the nature of this confrontation and as an accident, it could not be concluded that the officer's vehicle moved too fast. The standard to be applied was set out by the Saskatchewan Court of Queen's Bench in R. v. Kozun 1997 CanLII 11313. The Court reviewed four areas where there was inconsistency and conflict in the evidence given by the Crown and defence witnesses.  2) The accused said he thought the defendant was going too fast when"
