7_2011skpc143.txt,"The plaintiff filed a number of duplicate claims on behalf of a number of individuals. The issue was whether the claims should be issued. HELD: Section 7(1) of The Small Claims Act provides that a Provincial Court Judge acts as a gatekeeper to insure that claims comply with the Act before they are issued. In this role, the Provincial Court judge is exercising a quasi judicial function. Counsel for the plaintiff has clearly indicated that the claim is a test case. The plaintiff seeks declaratory relief. A substantial amount of the claim involves an allegation of breach of contract, but neither the plaintiff nor the proposed defendants were signatories to the contract. Accordingly, they would not be entitled to the benefit of the agreement. As virtually all of the potential issues raised by these claims are declaratory in nature, they are outside the jurisdiction of the Provincial Court. Any litigation over these issues must be done in the Court of Queen's Bench.","The defendant had submitted 18 claims for issuing by the defendant pursuant to the Small Claims Act. The defendant had refused to issue a summons and was in the process of remitting the matter to another Provincial Court Judge, who was out of the province at the time of this writing. The issues were important issues to the potential plaintiff, and may well be worth litigating, but that litigation, in my view, must be done in the Court of Queen’s Bench, by either issuing a new claim, or by way of enforcement proceedings of the claim upon which the agreement referenced above was made. The court reviewed the letter and found it was terse and complained about the speed at which the matter was being considered. It did not stipulate with any precision what damages have been suffered, nor establish any sort of quantum for those damages. HELD: The defendant was directed to provide notice to the other parties and provide notice of the date and times of his submission to the court. There was no obligation on the defendant to attend a pre-hearing conference."
2_1999canlii12669.txt,"The respondent seeks an order for interim spousal support. The parties were married in January 1991 with three children and ceased to cohabit in December of 1996. The respondent is 52 years old and unemployed. In the past, he has been diagnosed as paranoid schizophrenic and suffering from a personality disorder but is currently, according to his physician, of sound mind. He qualifies since 1987 for a disability pension under CPP by reason of his mental disability which provides for a basic income of $580 plus GTS rebate for a total of $630 per month. The petitioner lives on a section of farm land which was brought into the marriage by the respondent, of which one quarter contains the matrimonial home. The petitioner and children live in that home. The petitioner is 39 years old and is also unemployed because she is an incomplete quadriplegic. The farm land is rented out from which the petitioner receives rental income. The petitioner enjoys an income of $3,400 per month while the respondent receives $630 per month. HELD: The petitioner is ordered to pay the respondent the annual sum of $6,000 paid in monthly installments of $500. There is no juridical reason why the petitioner should obtain the total revenue owned by the respondent particularly when he brought the land into the marriage. In fact, fairness and equity would suggest just the opposite, at least in respect to one half of the revenue. Accordingly, the Court makes an order on the basis of the respondent's ownership of the land rather than order payment of spousal support.","FIAT The Respondent sought an order for interim spousal support. HELD: The Court ordered that the petitioner pay the respondent the annual sum of $6,000. The respondent was 52 years of age and unemployed. He had been diagnosed as paranoid schizophrenic and suffering from a personality disorder. His disability pension from the Canada Pension Plan was $580. He qualified for disability pension by reason of his mental disability. He lived with a friend and bought food for both of them. There was another source of income and property which the respondent had rented out. The petitioner disclosed much the same property but values it at $293,874. The difference in value relates to certain farmland which the petitioner brought into the marriage. The combination of the respondent's total pension income, including G.S.T. credit, along with the whole of the rental, would provide a monthly income of $630. The reasonable needs of the children would be met even if some of the landlord's payment was paid to the respondent. The Court noted that the respondent does not require financial assistance. He does not manage his finances well and reference was made to the fact that he spends over 25% of his present income on the luxuries of eating out, entertainment, recreation and cigarettes. The actual amount is $210 which is 33 per cent of his current income."
