ld have left without getting into a tug-of-war over the jacket. However, the evidence was inconclusive and the mother had not proven these allegations on the necessary balance of probabilities. HELD: 1)Joint custody does not mean that one parent has the right to micro-manage the daily care of a child by the other parent. The fact that there is no evidence the perpetrator has actually harmed the child is an insufficient reason to conclude the perpetrator presents no risk to his or her child. 2)The father was to attend a course in parenting such as those offered by Family SOS so that he will be better prepared to parent the child in the future. The evidence did not suggest he could not care for the child for two to three hour periods unsupervised.  3)There was no evidence that the father was under the influence of marijuana or that he was in any way influenced by the mother's allegations."
e_1996canlii7080.txt,"FIAT. The Crown applied to have a witness, who was an unindicted co-conspirator and separately charged with drug offences arising out of the same investigation, declared adverse pursuant to s9 of the Canada Evidence Act. She had contradicted her prior video taped statement made shortly after her arrest and had demonstrated hostile attitude towards the Crown. The defence took the position that she was now telling the truth; that the statement was improperly obtained in breach of the confession rules of voluntariness and the statement did not meet the requirements set out in R. v. K.G.B. HELD: The witness' prior statement may be introduced in evidence for the substantive truth of its contents. It will be for the jury to decide what, if any, portions of such statement they wish to accept. 1)A prior inconsistent statement cannot be introduced in evidence for its substantive content, unless the requirement of necessity, and a threshold of reliability arrived at on a balance of probabilities are established. When, as here, a witness recants, the requirement of necessity is established. The real issue is whether the prior statement meets the test for reliability. When, as here, there is only one demonstrably false piece of testimony in the statement, which does not implicate anyone but rather attempts to exonerate someone, the Court was not prepared to say ipso facto the statement is unreliable. 2)The independent evidence sufficiently corroborated her statement in enough different particulars that, but for the demonstrably false portion, it met the threshold of reliability.","FIAT. The Crown applied to have the accused declared adverse pursuant to s. 9 of the Canada Evidence Act on the basis that she has demonstrated ahostile attitude towards the position of the Crown, and hascontradicted in a substantial way, her prior video-taped statement to police officers made shortly after her arrest. The defence sought to use the prior statement, not only for the purposes of impeaching her credibility at trial, but also as substantive evidence that may be left with the jury at the end of the trial. HELD: The accused's prior statement was not unreliable. The oath administered prior to the taking of the statement did not place the accused's statement one step up from an unsworn statement. The reliability threshold is not met, even if the witness is sworn and warned prior to giving the statement, when it is subsequently known that at least portion of it is false. The fact that her motivation to do so was to help herself is a factor to be taken into account in assessing the reliability of her statement as it relates to third parties.  1)The evidence of an experienced cooperator was accepted along with the evidence of a person who had provided consistent testimony. 2)There was no discussion with the accused on the consequences of lying. 3)The oath administered post-sentence, accompanied by warning that the witness could be subject to perjury charges if the statement turned out to be untrue, did not meet the requirements set out in R. v. K.G.B. (1995). 4)The credibility test was not met. The statements could not be introduced in evidence for the substantive truth of their subjections. 5)The reliability threshold was not satisfied even if a witness was sworn and cautioned prior to providing the statement. Form should not override substance. The Court was satisfied that the oath was administered in accordance with the rules of voluntariness and that it met the threshold of reliability. It would be for the jury to decide after receiving appropriate instructions with respect to the evidence and evidence of that person who has provided inconsistent testimony, what, if any portions of such statement could be accepted."
e_1999canlii1479.txt,"The respondent was recruited by the respondents. Her job was to start quality assurance practice. She accepted an offer of employment, giving up her own company to do so. After 15 months she was dismissed. The trial judge in her action for wrongful dismissal and negligent misrepresentation did not find any negligent misrepresentation but awarded damages equivalent to five months notice for wrongful dismissal. The appellant appealed the dismissal of her claim for negligent misrepresentation and the notice period for her wrongful dismissal. The respondent cross-appealed the damage award, claiming the trial judge failed to take into account the appellant's failure to mitigate. Appeal and cross-appeal, that the evidence supports the trial judge's findings, and he did not make any errors in law.","The respondent cross-appealed for damages in an action for wrongful dismissal. The appellant contended the trial judge erred in failing to properly apply the principles of negligent misrepresentation as set out by the Supreme Court of Canada in Queen v. Cognos. Awarding the respondent $5 months pay in lieu of notice, that the five-month notice period was an effective disclaimer precluding any separate action in tort. The Court of Appeal reversed the judgment and dismissed the action on the basis that the misrepresentation was not 'negligent' and, in any event, the term in the contract providing for dismissal on notice was such a disclaimer that it did not constitute negligence. The trial judge did not accept the appellant's submissions that the respondents misrepresented the nature of the employment opportunity. HELD: The appeal could not succeed. 1)The trial judge failed to specifically address the arguments that the promise of job security and the assurance that she could work for the company until retirement, as well as the assurances of fair treatment, were inducements. Such inducements are properly included among the considerations which tend to lengthen the amount of notice.  2)The Court found that the conduct of the parties involved in the employment contract could not be concurrent with a duty defined by an express term of the contract. Strikingly, the Court held that the contractual provisions for notice did not bar an action in a tort case. 3)Although the appellant did not sign the contract, she was entitled to augmented damages because she was induced to leave her company and join KPMG and because the dismissal was in bad faith and the manner of the dismissal itself callous."
4_2005skqb542.txt,"The Government seeks an order pursuant to Rule 164(4) of the Queen's Bench Rules requiring the plaintiff to provide better particulars in response to its demand for particulars and pursuant to Rule 173 of the Rules and order striking portions of the pleadings. HELD: 1) The plaintiff has failed to identify the legislative scheme by which responsibility for education in Ile a la Crosse or specifically, responsibility for education of a group of people that included the plaintiff, was delegated to the Minister of Education or any other member of executive government. The Government is entitled to know the case it has to meet. If the plaintiff knows the statute and regulations on which he relies, he must provide particulars. If he does not have particulars of the statutes and regulations, he must so state. 2) The court was not prepared to strike the phrases 'without limiting the generality of the foregoing' and 'without limitation'. The conduct of examination for discovery and undertakings can provide the defendant with particulars of allegations to be made by the plaintiff in order to permit it to properly defend the action.  3) The Government demanded full particulars of the breach of trust and breach of fiduciary duty. The plaintiff's response does not lay a foundation for either and the paragraphs are struck.  4) The court was satisfied that exemplary damages and punitive damages were synonymous and therefore only one of them should be pled to avoid confusion. The court directed that any reference to exemplary damages should be read as to include punitive damages and that only one phrase should be used. 5) As the cause of action clearly predates the coming into force of The Pre-judgment Interest Act, the provisions of that Act have no application to the plaintiff's claim.","The Government of Saskatchewan sought an order pursuant to Queen's Bench Rule 164(4) requiring the plaintiff to provide better particulars in response to its demand for particulars, and in default of so doing striking the offending portions of the statement of claim. HELD: The order was reserved pending the decisions of the Supreme Court of Canada. The Government was entitled to make any additional arguments. 1) The pleadings do not lay foundation for breach of fiduciary duty or breach of trust.  2) The Government failed to identify the legislative scheme by which responsibility for education in Ile a la Crosse was delegated to the Minister of Education or any other member of executive government. The claim for 'punitive and exemplary damages' was dismissed. 3) The evidence did not support the claim for punitive damages. 4) There was no evidence that the government put its own interests ahead of those of the plaintiff in order to properly defend the action and not be taken by surprise.  5) In cases where there is a chance that the plaintiff might succeed, the plaintiff should not be driven from the judgment seat. If the plaintiff knows the statutes and regulations on which he relies, he must provide particulars of same."
